    "# 15.\tImagine you are woking with a laptop of 2GB RAM, how would you process a dataset of 10GB?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "b6f6a7f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Sub sampling - to reduce the size - not that much good answer\n",
    "# Cloud Computing AWS GCP(Google Cloud Platform) - more cost\n",
    "# Out of core ML - Technique is preferable"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8ae91a24",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Core Memory is RAM\n",
    "1. Stream data: Data read karke RAM mei lana in mini batches by dividing into chunks - data reader like Pandas\n",
    "2. Extract Features\n",
    "3. Train Model: incremental learning  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "3851683b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "🔹 Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 You have:\n",
    "\n",
    "2GB RAM laptop\n",
    "10GB dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 You cannot load entire data into memory\n",
    "\n",
    "So you must use memory-efficient techniques\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Key Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "Process data in chunks / streams instead of loading everything at once\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Solutions (Step-by-Step)\n",
    "✅ 1. Use Chunking (Most Important)\n",
    "📌 Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "Read data in small parts (chunks)\n",
    "\n",
    "🧠 Example (Python – Pandas)\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "for chunk in pd.read_csv(\"large_file.csv\", chunksize=10000):\n",
    "    process(chunk)   # your logic here\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Only a small part is loaded at a time\n",
    "👉 Memory stays within limit\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 2. Use Generators (Memory Efficient)\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of storing full data, use generators\n",
    "\n",
    "def read_data(file):\n",
    "    for line in open(file):\n",
    "        yield line\n",
    "\n",
    "for row in read_data(\"large_file.csv\"):\n",
    "    process(row)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Processes one row at a time\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 3. Use Incremental / Online Learning\n",
    "\n",
    "Some models support partial training\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "SGDClassifier\n",
    "Naive Bayes\n",
    "model.partial_fit(X_chunk, y_chunk)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Train model chunk by chunk\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 4. Use Sampling\n",
    "\n",
    "If full data is not required:\n",
    "\n",
    "df = pd.read_csv(\"large_file.csv\", nrows=100000)\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Use subset of data for quick analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 5. Use Database Instead of Memory\n",
    "\n",
    "Store data in:\n",
    "\n",
    "SQL database\n",
    "Query only required data\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "SELECT * FROM table LIMIT 10000;\n",
    "✅ 6. Use Efficient Data Types\n",
    "\n",
    "Reduce memory usage:\n",
    "\n",
    "df['col'] = df['col'].astype('int32')\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Smaller data types → less memory\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 7. Use External Libraries (Big Data Tools)\n",
    "Dask → works like pandas but handles large data\n",
    "PySpark → distributed processing\n",
    "✅ 8. Use Disk-Based Processing\n",
    "Store intermediate results on disk\n",
    "Use formats like:\n",
    "CSV → slow\n",
    "Parquet → faster & compressed\n",
    "✅ 9. Feature Selection / Reduction\n",
    "Remove unnecessary columns\n",
    "Reduce dimensionality\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Less data → less memory\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ 10. Use Compression\n",
    "Read compressed files directly\n",
    "pd.read_csv(\"file.csv.gz\")\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Saves disk + memory\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Beginner-Friendly Version\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Don’t try to load full data\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead:\n",
    "\n",
    "read small parts\n",
    "process one by one\n",
    "train model gradually\n",
    "🔹 Real-Life Analogy\n",
    "\n",
    "Like eating food:\n",
    "\n",
    "❌ Try to eat whole meal in one bite → impossible\n",
    "✅ Eat in small bites → easy\n",
    "🔹 Interview Answer (5 lines)\n",
    "\n",
    "If I have a 10GB dataset and only 2GB RAM, I would process the data in chunks instead of loading it entirely into memory. I can use techniques like chunking in pandas, generators, or incremental learning methods such as partial_fit. I may also use sampling or store data in a database to query required portions. Additionally, I can use tools like Dask or PySpark for handling large datasets efficiently. These approaches ensure memory-efficient processing without crashing the system.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Strong Practical Answer (Impress Interviewer)\n",
    "\n",
    "You can say:\n",
    "\n",
    "“I would combine chunk processing with incremental learning. For example, read data in chunks using pandas and train models using partial_fit, while optimizing memory using proper data types.”\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 One-Line Memory Trick\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Big data → process in chunks, not all at once\n",
    "\n",
    "🔥 Final Summary\n",
    "Don’t load full data\n",
    "Use chunking\n",
    "Use incremental learning\n",
    "Use efficient tools\n",
    "\n",
    "If you want next, I can give:\n",
    "🔥 System design question (ML pipeline for big data)\n",
    "🔥 Dask vs Spark comparison\n",
    "🔥 Real interview coding problems on large data handling\n",
    "\n",
    "Is there Out of core Machine Learning Technique to be used for best\n",
    "\n",
    "Yes buddy — this is exactly the right concept for your previous question 👍\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 What is Out-of-Core Machine Learning?\n",
    "📌 Definition\n",
    "\n",
    "Out-of-core learning is a technique where:\n",
    "\n",
    "models are trained on data that cannot fit into memory (RAM) by processing it in small chunks from disk.\n",
    "\n",
    "🧠 Core Idea\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Instead of loading full data (10GB), you:\n",
    "\n",
    "Load a small chunk\n",
    "Train/update model\n",
    "Discard chunk\n",
    "Load next chunk\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Repeat until all data is processed\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Why is it Best for Your Scenario?\n",
    "\n",
    "For your case:\n",
    "\n",
    "RAM = 2GB\n",
    "Data = 10GB\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Out-of-core learning is one of the best approaches because:\n",
    "\n",
    "Works with limited memory\n",
    "Scales to large datasets\n",
    "Avoids crashes\n",
    "🔹 How It Works (Pipeline)\n",
    "Data streaming (chunking)\n",
    "Feature extraction\n",
    "Incremental model training\n",
    "Repeat\n",
    "🔹 Algorithms That Support Out-of-Core Learning\n",
    "\n",
    "These models support incremental learning (partial_fit):\n",
    "\n",
    "✅ Linear Models\n",
    "SGDClassifier\n",
    "SGDRegressor\n",
    "✅ Probabilistic Models\n",
    "Naive Bayes\n",
    "✅ Neural Networks\n",
    "Some deep learning frameworks (mini-batch training)\n",
    "🔹 Example (Python)\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier\n",
    "\n",
    "model = SGDClassifier()\n",
    "\n",
    "for chunk in pd.read_csv(\"large_file.csv\", chunksize=10000):\n",
    "    X = chunk.drop(\"target\", axis=1)\n",
    "    y = chunk[\"target\"]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    model.partial_fit(X, y, classes=[0,1])\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Model learns chunk by chunk\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 Tools for Out-of-Core Learning\n",
    "📊 Libraries\n",
    "Scikit-learn → supports partial_fit\n",
    "Dask → large-scale pandas\n",
    "PySpark → distributed computing\n",
    "🔹 Advantages\n",
    "Works with very large datasets\n",
    "Memory efficient\n",
    "Scalable\n",
    "Suitable for streaming data\n",
    "🔹 Limitations\n",
    "Not all algorithms support it\n",
    "Requires careful tuning\n",
    "Slightly slower than in-memory training\n",
    "🔹 Out-of-Core vs Normal Training\n",
    "Feature\tOut-of-Core\tNormal Training\n",
    "Data size\tLarger than RAM\tFits in RAM\n",
    "Training\tIncremental\tBatch\n",
    "Memory usage\tLow\tHigh\n",
    "Scalability\tHigh\tLimited\n",
    "🔹 Beginner-Friendly Version\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Big data → don’t load everything\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead:\n",
    "\n",
    "take small pieces\n",
    "learn step by step\n",
    "🔹 Interview Answer (Perfect)\n",
    "\n",
    "Yes, out-of-core machine learning is the best approach when the dataset is larger than available RAM. It involves processing data in chunks and training models incrementally using methods like partial_fit. This allows the model to learn without loading the entire dataset into memory. Libraries like Scikit-learn, Dask, and PySpark support such workflows. It is highly memory-efficient and suitable for large-scale or streaming data.\n",
    "\n",
    "🔹 One-Line Memory Trick\n",
    "\n",
    "👉 Out-of-core = data outside RAM → learn in chunks\n",
    "\n",
    "🚀 Pro Tip (Impress Interviewer)\n",
    "\n",
    "You can say:\n",
    "\n",
    "“Out-of-core learning is essentially combining chunk processing with incremental learning to handle large datasets efficiently.”"
   ]
